<subSubSection id="C5DA6570FFC5FF980F83FBBA5B270193" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8D7F36FBFFC5FF980F83FBBA5B270193" blockId="3.[151,1437,941,1767]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis id="BFB4EAE9FFC5FF980F83FBBA580F011B" bold="true" box="[199,327,1061,1087]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Shell somewhat ovate to kidney-shaped, smooth; umbones terminal, prominent, somewhat coiled; siphons separate. The anterior retractor is fastened on the anterior thickened margin of the shell just below the umbones. The posterior adductor is small and the posterior retractor leaves a small scar above the adductor (
<bibRefCitation id="E9514B0AFFC5FF980E48FB025B2B0193" author="Soot-Ryen" box="[268,611,1181,1207]" pageId="3" pageNumber="44" refString="Soot-Ryen, T. (1955) A report on the family Mytilidae (Pelecypoda). Allan Hancock Pacific Expeditions, 20, 1 - 175." type="journal article" year="1955">
Soot-Ryen 
<number id="3B0824DCFFC5FF980ED6FB0258990193" box="[402,465,1181,1207]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="1955.0">1955</number>
: text-fig. 
<number id="3B0824DCFFC5FF980D05FB025B2B0193" box="[577,611,1181,1207]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="70.0">70</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
